rant workers were essential to the expansion of transnational capitalism and global ecological change. Bridging American, Chinese, and Pacific historiographies, Beyond Hawai‘i is the first book to argue that indigenous labor—more than the movement of ships and spread of diseases—unified the Pacific World.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aHawaiianszPacific AreaxHistory. 0aIndigenous laborxHistory. 7aHISTORY / World.2bisacsh  a1700s.  a1800s.  a18th century.  a19th century.  aarctic ocean.  acalifornia.  acapitalism.  acaptain james cook.  aenvironment.  aequatorial islands.  aexploration.  aexplorers.  aglobal ecological change.  aglobal ecology.  aglobal economy.  ahunting.  aindigenous labor.  aindigenous people.  akanaka maoli.  alife and death.  alife story.  amigrant workers.  amining.  anative hawaiian.  apacific ocean.  apacific world.  asugar plantations.  atransnational.  atravel.  atrue story.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z97831106676770 cprintz978052029506340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520967960423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520967960/original  a978-3-11-066767-7  University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles